name: The Liberation
message: Our friends Brendan Canty (of Fugazi) and Christoph Green, the DC-based documentary filmmakers who produced the Eddie Vedder Live - Water on the Road DVD and producers of the Burn to Shine film series, through their company Trixie, are trying to fund a film called The Liberation a documentary that follows two participants through a 14-week culinary training program at DC Central Kitchen, the country's oldest community kitchen.  A contribution will allow Canty and Green to shoot the entire 14 week program, to be present for the struggles and accomplishments of the students they are following, and to give the program and organization the coverage that it deserves, which is a formidable task.  To make a donation to the funding of this film (anything over $1 will help), please visit http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/895433958/the-liberation But please hurry. This project will only be funded if $40,000.00 is pledged by Thursday, January 26.

description: A film about two people's paths from prison, homelessness, and addiction, through a revolutionary kitchen training program in Wash DC.

name: Friendly Fire

data.message: There has been a lot of debate on this in the media lately. The best comment I've heard in a long time on this topic came from Dr. Nancy Snyderman on The Today Show last week. She said "we need to get rid of these labels & change them because SAHM are still working moms, just in a different sense.". If more people thought of it this way I think there wouldn't be as big of a debate.  I've been a working mom & a SAHM, and I say every day this is much harder than my corporate job was. Donny Deutsch said the same thing on The Today Show- he said 9 out of 10 of his partners are women & they all say they look forward to Monday because it is easier than their weekends. Every woman is different, but strong in what they choose to do.

Love this article and love the comments. Bridget, I'm right there with you. I have now done both and being home is way harder. I hate the guilt. Just like the article pointed out, I kicked my own ass while I was working and I do it now that I'm home. Maybe I'll give myself a break, if only for a week or so. ;)

Did I mention jump ticket prices could skyrocket?? DZs like Perris and San Diego ARE in controlled airspace, and both use SOCAL ATC services and turbine (not piston) aircraft! message:
The SOPA/PIPA dilemma really comes down to which kind of farmer you prefer.  

The first farmer has a rat problem in his barn, so he burns the entire barn to the ground to get rid of the rats, but he also loses everything else he has in the barn, as well as the insurance payout and the ability to run his farming operation.

The second farmer also has a rat problem in his barn.  Farmer #2 sprinkles poison in the corners of the barn where the rats are most likely to congregate and employs a few hungry cats to go hunting.  Most, but not all of the rats, are slowly eliminated, and the second farmer is still able to run his farming operation.

Soon, Congress will decide which kind of farmer to be, and we will all have the opportunity to decide whether their choice is acceptable with our votes in ten months.
